    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1895-05-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1895-05-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="87"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d87">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Willis</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Gresham</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Honolulu</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1895-05-02">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 2, 1895</hi>
                        </date>. (Received May 14.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 105.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: On the 29th ultimo I sent the following telegram,
                    which I now confirm: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>Your No. 65, of February 21, 1895, has just been received per <hi
                                rend="italic">Gaelic</hi> from Hongkong, marked “missent to
                            Hongkong.” Two other letters, one of which was from Washington, were
                            received inclosed as above.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>On the morning of the 30th ultimo I called upon Mr. Hatch, minister of foreign
                    affairs, and explained to him that on the previous afternoon I had found in my
                    box at the post-office a dispatch from you, indorsed with the words “missent to
                    Hongkong,” and on that morning I had received by steamer <hi rend="italic"
                        >Coptic</hi>, just arrived, a duplicate of the same dispatch, which I was
                    instructed to read to him in person. Thereupon I read to him your dispatch of
                    February 21 last, and left with him a copy of the same.</p>
                <p>It appears from newspaper clippings, which I inclose, that the subject-matter of
                    your dispatch was before the executive and advisory councils yesterday
                    afternoon. What conclusion, if any, was reached is unknown to me.</p>
                <p>With assurances, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Albert S. Willis.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
